III. Our Ordinations are better then  the Ordinations of Rome, if we consider the Persons ordained. That which we have said concerning the want of Qualifications in the Ordainers, may be also applied to the ordained in the Roman Communion. Their Priests are


made without the Election of the People;
                  Bellar. de Cler. lib. 1 cap. 7 & 8. and Bellarmine saith that neither their Suffragium, Concilium, or Consensus is required, which is contrary to Scripture, and Antiquity,Vid. Cypr. Ep. 68. Euseb. VI. 10. as our Protestant Writers have proved against the Papists. See Willet's Synops. Papismi, 5 Controver. Quest. 2. p. 260...

Bede himself acknowledges that the first Bishop the Scots had was Palladius, though they were Christians before; 
   Bed. I. 13. 
Palladius ad Scotos in Christum credentes à Pontifice Romanae Ecclesiae Celestino primus mittitur Episcopus. He did not make them Christians, but found them so.
